text:
The preponderant view - and Allah knows best - is that Mu'adh's reading with doubling is in the second {Al-Rashad} which is from the speech of the Believer; because there are those who specified it to the second letter (occurrence), like Abu Al-Fadl Al-Razi (1), and he is among the trustworthy scholars of readings, as well as Ibn Khalawayh (2). By this, what was problematic to Ibn Atiyyah is removed.
* * *
[34]: Ibn Atiyyah said speaking about the readings appearing in {Astaghfarta} (3) from His saying - the Exalted -: ... {It is all the same for them whether you ask forgiveness for them or do not ask forgiveness for them; never will Allah forgive them. Indeed, Allah does not guide the defiantly disobedient people}

Disbelief in Allah is but a pillar of the pillars of preventing from Islam, so He presented preventing from the way of Allah then followed with disbelief in Allah; to convey by indication of correspondence after He indicated it by preventing from the way of Allah by indication of inclusion. Then He counted against them preventing from the Sacred Mosque then expelling its people from it." (1)
2 - That His saying: {Wal-Masjidi Al-Harami} is conjoined to the Ha in {Bihi}, i.e.: Disbelief in Him and in the Sacred Mosque. Said by: Al-Baghawi (2), Abu Hayyan (3), Al-Samin Al-Halabi (4), and others (5). This opinion was weakened because conjoining without repeating the preposition is not permissible according to the majority of Basrans except in poetic necessity (6). The defenders replied that this is permissible according to the preponderant view; due to its occurrence in the Quran and in Arab speech (7).
Among its occurrences in the Quran: His saying: {Wa ma yutla 'alaykum} (8) from His saying - the Exalted -: ... {And they request from you a [legal] ruling concerning women. Say, "Allah gives you a ruling about them and [about] what has been recited to you in the Book concerning the orphan girls to whom you do not give what is decreed for them - and [yet] you desire to marry them} [Al-Nisa: 127]. His saying: {Wa ma yutla 'alaykum}
